            "description": "<p>A key, as opens a <a href=\"/door/\">door</a> or <a href=\"/locked/\">lock</a>. Depicted at a 45&deg; angle as a gold, bronze, or copper key with a round head and notched blade. Commonly used for figurative senses of <em>key</em>, e.g., <em>the key to success</em>, being<em> key</em>&nbsp;(&quot;crucial&quot;).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>DJ Khaled&nbsp;uses the emoji to indicate his&nbsp;<a href=\"http://snapchatemojis.com/verified/\">Snapchat stories are official</a> (verified). Apple&rsquo;s design <a href=\"/apple/ios-9.1/key/\">previously resembled</a> a gold <a href=\"/old-key/\">üóùÔ∏è Old Key</a>, which emoji has similar applications.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>May also represent digital keys in <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Public-key_cryptography\">public-key technology</a>. This may explain why the emoji&nbsp;<a href=\"https://blog.emojipedia.org/emojipedia-now-with-https/\">does not display in page titles</a>&nbsp;on&nbsp;Apple&rsquo;s Safari web browser, presumably to prevent less reputable sites from pretending to be secure (encrypted using&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HTTPS\">HTTPS</a>).</p>",
